      <div class="faq-section">
        <div class="section-eyebrow">FAQ</div>
        <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
        <div class="faq-list">

          <div class="faq-item">
            <button class="faq-question" aria-expanded="false">What is the FICA tax rate for 2025?<span class="faq-chevron"><svg width="12" height="12" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2.5"><polyline points="6 9 12 15 18 9"/></svg></span></button>
            <div class="faq-answer">For 2025, the FICA tax rate for employees is 7.65% total: 6.2% for Social Security on wages up to $176,100, and 1.45% for Medicare on all wages with no cap. Employers pay a matching 7.65%. High earners also pay an additional 0.9% Medicare tax on wages above $200,000.</div>
          </div>

          <div class="faq-item">
            <button class="faq-question" aria-expanded="false">What is the Social Security wage base for 2025?<span class="faq-chevron"><svg width="12" height="12" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2.5"><polyline points="6 9 12 15 18 9"/></svg></span></button>
            <div class="faq-answer">The 2025 Social Security wage base is $176,100. Once your year-to-date wages exceed this amount, Social Security tax stops being withheld for the rest of the year. Medicare tax has no wage base limit and continues on all wages regardless of total earnings.</div>
          </div>

          <div class="faq-item">
            <button class="faq-question" aria-expanded="false">Do self-employed people pay FICA?<span class="faq-chevron"><svg width="12" height="12" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2.5"><polyline points="6 9 12 15 18 9"/></svg></span></button>
            <div class="faq-answer">Yes, through self-employment tax. Self-employed individuals pay 15.3% on 92.35% of net self-employment earnings: 12.4% for Social Security up to $176,100 and 2.9% for Medicare with no limit. They can deduct half of the SE tax on their federal return, which partially offsets the burden.</div>
          </div>

          <div class="faq-item">
            <button class="faq-question" aria-expanded="false">Does FICA apply to all types of income?<span class="faq-chevron"><svg width="12" height="12" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2.5"><polyline points="6 9 12 15 18 9"/></svg></span></button>
            <div class="faq-answer">No. FICA applies to wages, salaries, and self-employment income. It does not apply to investment income like interest, dividends, capital gains, or rental income. However, high earners may owe the 3.8% Net Investment Income Tax on those types of income separately.</div>
          </div>

          <div class="faq-item">
            <button class="faq-question" aria-expanded="false">What happens if too much Social Security tax is withheld?<span class="faq-chevron"><svg width="12" height="12" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2.5"><polyline points="6 9 12 15 18 9"/></svg></span></button>
            <div class="faq-answer">If you work multiple jobs and your combined wages exceed $176,100, each employer withholds Social Security tax independently and you may have too much withheld in total. You can claim a credit for excess Social Security tax withheld on your federal return, which reduces your tax liability or increases your refund.</div>
          </div>

          <div class="faq-item">
            <button class="faq-question" aria-expanded="false">Are FICA taxes the same as federal income tax?<span class="faq-chevron"><svg width="12" height="12" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2.5"><polyline points="6 9 12 15 18 9"/></svg></span></button>
            <div class="faq-answer">No. FICA taxes and federal income tax are separate. FICA funds Social Security and Medicare specifically. Federal income tax is calculated using tax brackets and funds the general federal budget. Both are withheld from your paycheck but calculated independently. Your W-2 shows each separately in different boxes.</div>
          </div>

        </div>
      </div>

